:44\" group=\"note\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | April 16\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |550\n| 382\n| 1605\n| 21\n| 4245\n| 170\n| 1985\n| 248\n| 7206\n| 3342\n| 2466\n| 6820\n| 2503\n| 638\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |18\n| 26\n| 63\n|\n| 159\n| 25\n| 164\n| 5\n| 258\n| 173\n| 99\n| 132\n| 110\n| 13\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":45\" group=\"note\"/>\n|-\n ! style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | Date\n ! {{vert header|Barnstable}}\n ! {{vert header|Berkshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Bristol}}\n ! {{vert header|Dukes and Nantucket}}\n ! {{vert header|Essex}}\n ! {{vert header|Franklin}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampden}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Middlesex}}\n ! {{vert header|Norfolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Plymouth}}\n ! {{vert header|Suffolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! {{vert header|Barnstable| cellstyle=border-left: 2px solid #888;}}\n ! {{vert header|Berkshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Bristol}}\n ! {{vert header|Dukes and Nantucket}}\n ! {{vert header|Essex}}\n ! {{vert header|Franklin}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampden}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Middlesex}}\n ! {{vert header|Norfolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Plymouth}}\n ! {{vert header|Suffolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |Source\n|-\n| style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | <strong>County <br/> pop <br/> (2020)</strong>\n| {{vert header|213,413}}\n| {{vert header|126,348}}\n| {{vert header|564,022}}\n| {{vert header|28,679}}\n| {{vert header|790,638}}\n| {{vert header|70,963}}\n| {{vert header|470,406}}\n| {{vert header|161,355}}\n| {{vert header|1,614,714}}\n| {{vert header|705,388}}\n| {{vert header|518,132}}\n| {{vert header|807,252}}\n| {{vert header|830,839}}\n| style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\"|\n| {{vert header|213,413}}\n| {{vert header|126,348}}\n| {{vert header|564,022}}\n| {{vert header|28,679}}\n| {{vert header|790,638}}\n| {{vert header|70,963}}\n| {{vert header|470,406}}\n| {{vert header|161,355}}\n| {{vert header|1,614,714}}\n| {{vert header|705,388}}\n| {{vert header|518,132}}\n| {{vert header|807,252}}\n| {{vert header|830,839}}\n|\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.massachusetts-demographics.com/counties_by_population |access-date = April 6, 2020 | title = Massachusetts Counties by Population | website= Massachusetts Demographics}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Government response ==\n[[File:ASM show at BCEC.agr.jpg|thumb|Interior of the [[Boston Convention and Exposition Center]] (BCEC), pictured during a 2016 conference. The BCEC will be converted to a [[field hospital]].]]\n\nCiting the rapid increase in cases, Governor Charlie Baker declared a [[state of emergency]] for Massachusetts on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/governor-charlie-baker-declares-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-3-10-2020/31356404 | title = Gov. Baker declares state of emergency as Mass. coronavirus cases more than double | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Locke | first = Kaitlyn | url = https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/10/baker-declares-state-of-emergency-92-total-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts | title = Baker Declares State Of Emergency; 92 Total Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WGBH News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> During a press conference on March 14, 2020, Governor Baker established an emergency command center and promised to expand statewide lab testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/14/metro/baker-sets-up-virus-command-center/|title=State figures on testing raise questions about efforts to contain outbreak |website=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker banned all public gatherings of over 25 people, closed all K\u201312 public schools from March 17 through April 7, and banned on-site service at bars and restaurants for the same period.<ref>{{cite news | title = Gov. Baker bans gatherings of over 25 people, orders school closure, restaurants take-out only | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/gov-charlie-baker-massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-15-2020/31647097 | access-date = March 17, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Governor Baker ordered all schools and childcare services to be closed through May 4, extending the original closure by three weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-extension-of-school-and-non-emergency-child-care-program|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Extension of School and Non-Emergency Child Care Program Closures and Steps to Ensure Housing Stability To Support COVID-19 Response|author= Office of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|publisher=Mass.gov|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced a stay-at-home advisory to be effective from March 24 until April 7. On March 31 the advisory which was extended to May 4.<ref name=\"Feuer\"/> Starting March 31, hotels, motels and online rentals like [[Airbnb]] were ordered to close to recreational travelers so they could be used to house essential workers and displaced residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-extends-non-essential-business-closures-and-executive-branch|title=Baker-Polito Administration Extends Non-Essential Business Closures and Executive Branch Employee Guidance|publisher=Mass.gov}}</ref> The [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] is being prepared as a 1,000-bed [[field hospital]] for COVID-19 patients, including 500 beds for infected homeless patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/02/1000-beds-planned-for-boston-convention-center-to-treat-coronavirus-patients|title=1,000 Beds Planned For Boston Convention Center To Treat Coronavirus Patients|date=April 2, 2020|first=Ally|last=Jarmanning|publisher=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[DCU Center]] in Worcester was set up as a field hospital for recovering COVID-19 patients, overseen by [[UMass Memorial Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/31/dcu-arena-covid-19-field-hospital|title=Worcester's DCU Center Will Become 250-Bed Field Hospital For Stable COVID-19 Patients|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Governor Baker asked travelers from out of state to avoid Massachusetts or to self-quarantine upon arrival for 14 days. Electronic highway signs were activated, and travelers arriving at [[Logan International Airport]], [[Worcester Regional Airport]], and [[South Station]] were given flyers.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/27/baker-out-of-state-quarantine|title=Baker Asks Visitors To Self-Isolate For Two Weeks \u2014 Or Not Come At All|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref> Medical students were graduated early, and emergency orders were issued giving some nurses with more than two years of experience authority to write prescriptions, and granting incoming medical residents and interns 90-day medical licenses.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\"/>\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Registry of Motor Vehicles]] moved to an appointment-only system to avoid overcrowding, and the state extended deadlines for many renewals by 60 days to reduce the need for in-person transactions. With visits down about 90%, eight of the 30 RMV branches closed completely. The National Association of Government Employees, representing customer service employees at the RMV, asked that the remaining offices be closed for worker safety, but the Secretary of Transportation said essential workers needed the RMV to continue operating.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/rmv-workers-union-calls-agency-shutter-all-branches/ RMV workers union calls for agency to shutter all branches]</ref>\n\n== Economic and social effects ==\nThe sudden surge of cases in Massachusetts during the week of March 9 led many organizations to order employees to work from home, and prompted museums and libraries to close. This led to a noticeable decline in Boston's rush hour traffic; in some cases, drive times for major highways dropped by 30 to 50 percent.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/11/boston-traffic-coronavirus | title = Coronavirus: Here's how much Boston's rush hour traffic has dropped &#124; Boston.com | website = Boston.com}}</ref> [[Panic buying]], especially since the week of March 11, led to shortages of some products, and there were crowds and long lines at grocery stores as early in the day as 7:00{{Nbsp}}a.m.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/store-shelves-picked-clean-people-panic-buy-goods-local-supermarkets/ | title = Store shelves picked clean as people panic-buy goods at local supermarkets |newspaper= The Boston Globe | access-date = April 6, 2020 | date= March 13, 2020 | first= Steve |last=Annear |first2=Janelle |last2=Nanos}}</ref> Some grocery retailers such as [[Stop & Shop]] adjusted their hours to allow employees more time to restock and to offer older and more vulnerable people a time where they can shop separately.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-stop-and-shop-senior-hours/ |title=Stop & Shop Creates Hours Only For Customers 60 And Older During Coronavirus Pandemic |date=March 16, 2020 |website=CBS Boston}}</ref> Later, grocery stores implemented stricter measures, including limiting the amount of people allowed inside stores at a time, and marking queues to maintain social distancing. <!--- https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/01/coronavirus-market-basket-social-distance/ ---> When people in parks were found to not be following social distancing resulted in many parks and playgrounds being closed. Some cities went as far as to remove or block off basketball hoops and other amenities to discourage people from gathering. <!--- https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/29/marty-walsh-boston-parks-coronavirus ---> Beaches and their parking lots were also ordered to close. <!--- https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/02/metro/parking-lots-state-beaches-are-closing/ ---> On April 5, 2020, Boston's mayor, Marty Walsh, issued a stay-at-home advisory for the city of Boston. All non-essential workers were ordered to stay home from 9:00{{Nbsp}}p.m. to 6:00{{Nbsp}}a.m., starting April 6. People were encouraged to wear masks when outside the home, but instructed to leave medical masks for essential workers and make their own if necessary. All baseball, tennis, and hockey fields in parks were ordered to be closed. Residents were instructed not to visit family or fields outside of their households. The restrictions are enforceable by fines.<ref name=\"WGBH-Curfew\"/>\n\n{{As of|2020|04|10|df=US|alt=As of April 10}}, eight deaths have been reported at Jack Satter House in [[Revere, Massachusetts|Revere]], a nursing home run by Hebrew Senior Life. Other nursing homes are also reporting confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boston-area senior housing community with Jewish ties reports 6 coronavirus deaths |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/boston-area-senior-housing-community-under-jewish-auspices-reports-6-coronavirus-deaths |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus cases at senior centers and nursing homes in Massachusetts are rising: 'It's a hot zone' - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/01/nation/covid-deaths-senior-centers-nursing-homes-rise/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hebrewseniorlife.org/about-us/covid-19-coronavirus-guidance/jack-satter-house-covid-19-update|title=Jack Satter House - COVID-19 Update|last=|first=|date=|website=Hebrew Senior Life|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== School closures ===\nSchool closures began in early March, when Massachusetts Institute of Technology announced on March 9 that it was moving to only-online classes for the remainder of the spring semester.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\"/> Also on March 9, two elementary schools in the [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]] school district and one in [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] were closed for the day due to COVID-19 tests being conducted on two parents and one child.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cuoco | first = John | url = https://whdh.com/news/multiple-massachusetts-schools-closed-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-rise/ | title = Multiple Massachusetts schools closed Monday as coronavirus cases continue to rise | date = March 9, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> School districts began closing on March 11. Within a week, many colleges and state school districts announced closures ranging from weeks to months in duration.<ref name=\"Williams-Update\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/massachusetts-coronavirus-update-schools-closing-or-changing-schedules-for-monday-march-16.html|title=Massachusetts coronavirus update: Schools closing or changing schedules for Monday, March 16|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 13, 2020|website=MassLive|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams-Colleges\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-and-massachusetts-updated-list-of-massachusetts-colleges-with-canceled-classes-plans-to-switch-to-online-instruction-march-13.html|title=Coronavirus and Massachusetts: Updated list of Massachusetts colleges with canceled classes, plans to switch to online instruction (March 13)|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\nWellesley and Framingham closed their public schools and libraries for two weeks on March 13.<ref>{{cite web | title = WPS Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/wps-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Town of Wellesley COVID-19 Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/town-of-wellesley-covid-19-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=2023 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/DocumentCenter/View/37162/Press-Release---COVID-19-Update-031320204265 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 13, Boston announced that its public schools would close for six weeks from Tuesday, March 17 through April 26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Boston Public Schools to close Tuesday, with plans to reopen April 27 | website = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/mayor-walsh-address-coronavirus-outbreak-friday-evening/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker ordered all schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17 through April 7.<ref name=\"Becker\"/> On March 25, he extended the closing through May 4.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baker: schools to open no sooner than May 4th |url=https://www.westernmassnews.com/news/baker-schools-to-open-no-sooner-than-may/article_dfa2979c-6ed0-11ea-8d2f-9f9402f5677e.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=www.westernmassnews.com |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12, and [[Major League Baseball]] canceled the remainder of spring training. On March 16, after the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] recommended restricting events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, the major league baseball season was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back | title = Opening of regular season to be pushed back | first = Mark | last = Feinsand | website = [[MLB.com]] | date = March 16, 2020 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games | title = Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days | date = March 12, 2020 | website = ESPN.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[National Hockey League]] season was suspended indefinitely.<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> Boston Celtics player [[Marcus Smart]] announced on March 18 that he had tested positive for COVID-19, having been tested five days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/boston-celtics-player-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-team-confirms/31792637|title=Celtics' Marcus Smart tests positive for coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|website=WCVB|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], which was originally scheduled to take place on April 20, was postponed to September 14. This was the first postponement of the Boston Marathon since it was first held in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/28897435/boston-marathon-postponed-sept-14-amid-coronavirus-concerns|title = Boston Marathon postponed until Sept. 14 amid coronavirus concerns|website = ESPN|date = March 13, 2020|accessdate = March 31, 2020}}</ref> Baker cautioned runners to refrain from running the route on Marathon Monday in April.\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n* [https://www.mass.gov/resource/information-on-the-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Coronavirus information] from the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]]\n* {{cite web | title=COVID-19 Information and Resources | website=[[Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education]] | url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/sfs/emergencyplan/covid19.html }}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|C