cording to the report [[published]] by [[Census India]] in 2011. The literacy rate of the village is 49.12%, lower than the state average of 75.84%. The population of children under the age of 6 years is 112 which is 14.47% of total population of the village, and child sex ratio is approximately 965 higher than the state average of 846.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_Village_Release_0300.xlsx|title=DCHB Village Release|work=[[Census of India, 2011]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of villages in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gurdaspur district}}\n\n{{coord|31|55|N|75|04|E|display=title|region:IN_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Gurdaspur district]]\n\n\n{{PunjabIN-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SDZeroBot", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stub sorting: replacing PunjabIN-geo-stub with Gurdaspur-geo-stub", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandu_Suja"}
{"title_page": "Andy Cameron", "text_new": "{{short description|British comedian and broadcaster}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2008}}\n{{lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Sections|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| name          = Andy Cameron\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1940|06|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Paris]], France, \n| death_date     =\n| othername     =\n| occupation    = [[Comedian]]\n| yearsactive   =\n| spouse        = \n| website       =\n| education     = \n| alma mater   = \n}}\n\n'''Andrew Graham Cameron''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 1940) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[comedian]], [[Television presenter|television]] and [[Radio presenter|radio broadcaster]].\n\nHe was born in London while his father, Hugh Cameron, was serving in the [[British Army|Army]] during [[World War II]]. Cameron was raised by his grandmother, Isabella 'Bella' Cameron, in the [[Royal burgh|Royal Burgh]] of [[Rutherglen]], south-east of [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/I+HATED+SCHOOL+SO+MUCH+I+PULLED+IT+DOWN%3B+David%27s+revenge+for+boring...-a072578187|title=I hated school so much I pulled it down|newspaper=Sunday Mail|via=The Free Library|date=1 April 2001|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=hubbard>[https://www-tmp.thenational.scot/sport/17867985.andy-cameron-johnny-hubbard-beat-eight-celtic-players-two-polis-steward/ Andy Cameron on Johnny Hubbard's historic hat-trick against Celtic], The National, 30 August 2019</ref> Prior to pursuing this career he had worked for a time with the Glasgow-based structural engineering firm, [[Sir William Arrol & Co.]] and for Glasgow Corporation Transport.\n\nHe entered [[show business]] when he was 32, initially working in [[nightclub|clubs]]. His act as a [[football hooligan]] led to him becoming a top comedy act in Scottish [[football (soccer)|football]] clubs. He is probably best known for writing and performing the football [[anthem]] \"[[Ally's Tartan Army]]\" for the [[Scotland national football team]]'s appearance at the [[1978 World Cup]]. It went to #6 in the [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book| first= David| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]| edition= 19th| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited| location= London| isbn= 1-904994-10-5| page= 90}}</ref> and led to two appearances on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' in 1978. Cameron promptly put all of the profits from his [[single (music)|single]] into producing an [[album]], which he hoped to release while the World Cup fever in Scotland was still going strong. He was too late - Scotland team went out of the World Cup early and Cameron's album fared equally badly. Andy also released a song in the 70's for his beloved Glasgow Rangers - 'The Greatest Team of All' - which still appears on the odd Rangers compilation album.\n\nIn 1975 he came second in ''[[New Faces]]'' leading to several appearances on variety shows such as ''Live at Her Majesty\u2019s'' with [[Jimmy Tarbuck]] and ''Tarby and Friends''.\n\nIn 1979, soon after the establishment of [[BBC Radio Scotland]], he was given a thirteen-week contract to present a programme of [[music]] and [[humour]]. The show eventually ran for fifteen years. He was voted Radio Personality of the year in 1984. He had his own series on [[BBC Scotland]] in 1979 and again in 1982. He was awarded Scottish Television Personality of the Year for his 1983 series called ''It\u2019s Andy Cameron''.\n\nIn the early 1980s he was invited to speak in debates at [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] and [[Oxford University|Oxford Universities]] alongside [[Arnold Brown (comedian)|Arnold Brown]] and [[James Naughtie]].\n\nIn 1984, Cameron presented [[STV (TV network)|STV]]'s ''[[Hogmanay]]'' show. The following year he presented the BBC Scotland Hogmanay show, and continued to do so until 1989. His last Hogmanay appearance was in 1990, in a short programme called ''Andy's Scottish Filling'' which preceded the live BBC Hogmanay Show.\n\nIn 1994 Cameron joined the cast of ''[[Take the High Road]]'', the STV [[soap opera|soap]]. He played a character called Chic Cherry, until the last episode in 2003.\n\nCameron is a well-known celebrity [[fan (person)|supporter]] of [[Rangers F.C.]]<ref name=hubbard/> In the early 1980s he caused some controversy by attacking the club's [[Rangers F.C. signing policy|anti-catholic signing policies]] at an [[Annual General Meeting]] of the club. He has a 'stand-up' act before Rangers' home league matches. In 1999, a follower of [[Aberdeen F.C.\u2013Rangers F.C. rivalry|rival]] club [[Aberdeen F.C.]] ran from the away section at [[Ibrox Stadium]] to assault Cameron as he performed a routine on the pitch prior to kick-off \u2013 the assailant was banned by the club and fined at court.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/345952.stm|title=Fan fined for comedian attack |publisher=BBC|website=[[BBC News]]|date=17 May 1999|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe currently works as an [[after dinner speaker]]. Furthermore, he presented a show on [[Clyde 2]] on Sunday afternoons until that show ended in late 2009 when he was replaced by Tom Ferrie, whose show is now networked by two or three others Scottish radio stations.\n\nCameron was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2015 New Year Honours for services to entertainment and charity in Glasgow.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61092|supp=y|page=N17|date=31 December 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/391413/New_Year_Honours_List_2015.pdf 2015 New Year Honours List]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tmcentertainment.co.uk/speaker-index.html?speakerid=6&speakertypeid=37 Profile], at Speak Out, a division of TMC Corporate Events & Entertainment Ltd\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cameron, Andy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:People from Rutherglen]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rutherglen Academy]]\n[[Category:Scottish radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n[[Category:Scottish stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Scottish male television actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish television presenters]]\n[[Category:People from Thorntonhall]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British comedian and broadcaster}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2008}}\n{{lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Sections|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| name          = Andy Cameron\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1940|06|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[London]], England, UK\n| death_date     =\n| othername     =\n| occupation    = [[Comedian]]\n| yearsactive   =\n| spouse        = \n| website       =\n| education     = \n| alma mater   = \n}}\n\n'''Andrew Graham Cameron''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 1940) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[comedian]], [[Television presenter|television]] and [[Radio presenter|radio broadcaster]].\n\nHe was born in London while his father, Hugh Cameron, was serving in the [[British Army|Army]] during [[World War II]]. Cameron was raised by his grandmother, Isabella 'Bella' Cameron, in the [[Royal burgh|Royal Burgh]] of [[Rutherglen]], south-east of [[Glasgow]], Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/I+HATED+SCHOOL+SO+MUCH+I+PULLED+IT+DOWN%3B+David%27s+revenge+for+boring...-a072578187|title=I hated school so much I pulled it down|newspaper=Sunday Mail|via=The Free Library|date=1 April 2001|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=hubbard>[https://www-tmp.thenational.scot/sport/17867985.andy-cameron-johnny-hubbard-beat-eight-celtic-players-two-polis-steward/ Andy Cameron on Johnny Hubbard's historic hat-trick against Celtic], The National, 30 August 2019</ref> Prior to pursuing this career he had worked for a time with the Glasgow-based structural engineering firm, [[Sir William Arrol & Co.]] and for Glasgow Corporation Transport.\n\nHe entered [[show business]] when he was 32, initially working in [[nightclub|clubs]]. His act as a [[football hooligan]] led to him becoming a top comedy act in Scottish [[football (soccer)|football]] clubs. He is probably best known for writing and performing the football [[anthem]] \"[[Ally's Tartan Army]]\" for the [[Scotland national football team]]'s appearance at the [[1978 World Cup]]. It went to #6 in the [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book| first= David| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]| edition= 19th| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited| location= London| isbn= 1-904994-10-5| page= 90}}</ref> and led to two appearances on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' in 1978. Cameron promptly put all of the profits from his [[single (music)|single]] into producing an [[album]], which he hoped to release while the World Cup fever in Scotland was still going strong. He was too late - Scotland team went out of the World Cup early and Cameron's album fared equally badly. Andy also released a song in the 70's for his beloved Glasgow Rangers - 'The Greatest Team of All' - which still appears on the odd Rangers compilation album.\n\nIn 1975 he came second in ''[[New Faces]]'' leading to several appearances on variety shows such as ''Live at Her Majesty\u2019s'' with [[Jimmy Tarbuck]] and ''Tarby and Friends''.\n\nIn 1979, soon after the establishment of [[BBC Radio Scotland]], he was given a thirteen-week contract to present a programme of [[music]] and [[humour]]. The show eventually ran for fifteen years. He was voted Radio Personality of the year in 1984. He had his own series on [[BBC Scotland]] in 1979 and again in 1982. He was awarded Scottish Television Personality of the Year for his 1983 series called ''It\u2019s Andy Cameron''.\n\nIn the early 1980s he was invited to speak in debates at [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] and [[Oxford University|Oxford Universities]] alongside [[Arnold Brown (comedian)|Arnold Brown]] and [[James Naughtie]].\n\nIn 1984, Cameron presented [[STV (TV network)|STV]]'s ''[[Hogmanay]]'' show. The following year he presented the BBC Scotland Hogmanay show, and continued to do so until 1989. His last Hogmanay appearance was in 1990, in a short programme called ''Andy's Scottish Filling'' which preceded the live BBC Hogmanay Show.\n\nIn 1994 Cameron joined the cast of ''[[Take the High Road]]'', the STV [[soap opera|soap]]. He played a character called Chic Cherry, until the last episode in 2003.\n\nCameron is a well-known celebrity [[fan (person)|supporter]] of [[Rangers F.C.]]<ref name=hubbard/> In the early 1980s he caused some controversy by attacking the club's [[Rangers F.C. signing policy|anti-catholic signing policies]] at an [[Annual General Meeting]] of the club. He has a 'stand-up' act before Rangers' home league matches. In 1999, a follower of [[Aberdeen F.C.\u2013Rangers F.C. rivalry|rival]] club [[Aberdeen F.C.]] ran from the away section at [[Ibrox Stadium]] to assault Cameron as he performed a routine on the pitch prior to kick-off \u2013 the assailant was banned by the club and fined at court.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/345952.stm|title=Fan fined for comedian attack |publisher=BBC|website=[[BBC News]]|date=17 May 1999|accessdate=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe currently works as an [[after dinner speaker]]. Furthermore, he presented a show on [[Clyde 2]] on Sunday afternoons until that show ended in late 2009 when he was replaced by Tom Ferrie, whose show is now networked by two or three others Scottish radio stations.\n\nCameron was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2015 New Year Honours for services to entertainment and charity in Glasgow.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61092|supp=y|page=N17|date=31 December 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/391413/New_Year_Honours_List_2015.pdf 2015 New Year Honours List]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tmcentertainment.co.uk/speaker-index.html?speakerid=6&speakertypeid=37 Profile], at Speak Out, a division of TMC Corporate Events & Entertainment Ltd\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cameron, Andy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:People from Rutherglen]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rutherglen Academy]]\n[[Category:Scottish radio personalities]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n[[Category:Scottish stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Scottish male television actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish television presenters]]\n[[Category:People from Thorntonhall]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish singers]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:2e07:6c01:18e7:6d3e:bbd0:d454", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_Cameron"}
{"title_page": "Chandu Nangal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Chandu Nangal\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = Village\n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|32|01|39.50|N|75|01|38.30|E|display=title,inline}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Gurdaspur district|Gurdaspur]]\n| subdivision_type3       = Tehsil\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Dera Baba Nanak]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Region\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Majha]]\n| government_type         = [[Panchayati raj (India)|Panchayat raj]]\n| governing_body          = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref>tags -->\n| elevation_m             = \n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_blank2_title = Total Households\n| population_blank2      = 63\n| population_footnotes    =\n| population_total        = 336<br/><small>171/165 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]</small>\n| population_density_km2  = \n| population_note         = \n| population_blank1_title = Scheduled Castes\n| population_blank1      = 145<br/><small>75/70 [[male|\u2642]]/[[female|\u2640]]</small>\n| population_demonym      = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| demographics1_title2    = \n| demographics1_info2     = \n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_total_ha           = 58\n| area_code_type          = Telephone\n| area_code               = 01871<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-18|title=Telephone directory of Gurdaspur district|url=http://gurdaspur.nic.in/html/telephone_directory.htm|website=gurdaspur.nic.in|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214111246/http://gurdaspur.nic.in/html/telephone_directory.htm|archive-date=14 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| registration_plate      =\n| iso_code                = IN-PB\n| blank1_name_sec2        = \n| blank1_info_sec2        = \n| website                 = {{URL|gurdaspur.nic.in}}\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n'''Chandu Nangal''' is a village in [[Dera Baba Nanak]] in [[Gurdaspur district]] of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] [[States and territories of India|State]], India. It is located {{convert|1|km}} from sub district headquarter and {{convert|40|km}} from district headquarter. The village is [[Administration (government)|administrated]] by [[Sarpanch]] an elected representative of the village.\n\n== Demography ==\n{{as of|2011}}, The village has a total number of 63 houses and the population of 336 of which 171 are males while 165 are females.<ref name=census>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_Village_Release_0300.xlsx|title=DCHB Village Release|work=[[Census of India, 2011]]}}</ref>  According to the report [[published]] by [[Census India]] in 2011, out of the total population of the village 145 people are from [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Schedule Caste]] and the village does not have any [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Schedule Tribe]] population so far.<ref name=census /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=103437|title=Child Sex Ratio in India (2001-2011)|work=pib.nic.in}}</ref><ref name=census />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of villages in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.punjabtourism.